Requirements and installation
*****************************

   @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub} requires @{b}Kickstart@{ub} and @{b}Workbench 2.04@{ub} (@{b}WB 2.1@{ub} if you want
to use localization) or higher to run. Also, you need @{b}MUI 2.0@{ub}, which is
available in many BBS.

   To install @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub} do the following:

   @{b}*@{ub} Drag the @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub} icon to the drawer you want to install the
     program on.

   @{b}*@{ub} If you want to use localization, copy the @{b}Catalogs@{ub} directory to
     your @{b}LOCALE:Catalogs@{ub} directory.

   This is all you have to do... However, in the next release I will
include an Installer script, for fast and easy installation.


@EndNode

@Node "Main window" "MUI-FReq.guide/Main window"
@Next "Configuration window"
@Prev "Requirements and installation"
@Toc "Main"

Main window
***********

   The main window consists of three areas, from the top to the bottom.

   @{b}*@{ub} Just below the window title, you can see a message area, where
     @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub} displays errors or other messages for the user.

   @{b}*@{ub} Below, you have the filelist and the related gadgets, that lets
     you manage the file names to be requested. Gadgets description
     follows:

     @{b}Fido address@{ub} lets you to specify the fidonet node you want to edit
     the filelist for. The address must be in the form @{i}z:n/f.p@{ui}, where
     z, n, f and p are decimal numbers. To allow @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub} recognize the
     address change, press RETURN when you have edited the address. Do
     not use TAB or the mouse, or the address won't be accepted. The
     popup gadget near the address will scan the Outbound directory for
     pending filerequests. Each node that has a @{b}.REQ@{ub} file (or a backup)
     will be displayed. Double-clicking on an entry will change the
     current address and load the proper filelist.

     If you start @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub} from CLI, you can insert in the command line
     a default value for this gadget. For example, @{i}MUI-FReq 2:332/113.0@{ui}
     will start the program with @{i}2:332/113.0@{ui} as the default node. This
     is expecially useful if you substitute @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub} to one of the
     built-in filerequest tools of fidonet editors like @{b}Mail Manager@{ub} or
     @{b}Spot@{ub}.

     @{b}Add@{ub} will add a new filename to the list, and activate the filename
     string gadget, to allow you editing of the name. Press RETURN to
     insert the filename, and @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub} will be ready to accept another
     filename. When you have finished, just press RETURN on the empty
     filename string.

     @{b}Remove@{ub} will delete the selected entry from the filelist. This can
     also be done by selecting a file, clearing the filename string
     gadget with Amiga-X and pressing RETURN.

     @{b}Up@{ub} will move up the selected entry.

     @{b}Down@{ub} will move down the selected entry.

     @{b}Sort@{ub} will sort the filename list alphabetically.

     @{b}Clear@{ub} will clear the whole filelist.

   @{b}*@{ub} Then, you have the action gadgets, that allows you to do various
     useful things:

     @{b}Load list@{ub} will load (if exists) the filelist for the current
     address. A proper message will be displayed in the message area.

     @{b}Save list@{ub} will save the current filelist in the form of a @{b}.REQ@{ub} file
     for the current address. If the current filelist is empty, the
     @{b}.REQ@{ub} file will bel deleted.

     @{b}Poll@{ub} will execute the configured poll command, in order to call the
     current node. The filelist will be saved before polling.

     @{b}Node Info@{ub} will pop up a requester with some useful informations
     about the current node. This function is available only if you
     have installed the @{b}traplist.library@{ub} which is distributed  with the
     @{b}TrapDoor@{ub} mailer.

     @{b}Scan Inbound@{ub} will check for every name in the current filelist if
     there is the corresponding file in the Inbound directory. If a
     file is found, it will be removed from the filelist. Very useful!

     @{b}Configuration...@{ub} will open the configuration panel. See
     @{"Configuration window" Link "Configuration window"}.

     @{b}About...@{ub} will show you some useful informations about the author.


@EndNode

@Node "Configuration window" "MUI-FReq.guide/Configuration window"
@Next "Acknowledgments"
@Prev "Main window"
@Toc "Main"

Configuration window
********************

   The configuration window lets you specify the paths and the options
for @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub}. It is divided into two sections, explained below.

   @{b}*@{ub} The paths and options gadgets. They are:

     @{b}Outbound path@{ub} is the same path configured in your mailer for the
     outbound files.  It is where files to be sent are kept.

     @{b}Inbound path@{ub} is the same path configured in your mailer for the
     inbound files.  It is where files received are kept.

     @{b}Poll command@{ub} is the command string to be executed in order to call
     your mailer.  If you place a @{i}%s@{ui} in the command string, it will be
     substituted by the Fidonet address of the node to be called, in
     the form @{i}z:n/f.p@{ui}.

     @{b}Use filelist backups@{ub} allows you to save and load backups for the
     filelists. They are saved as @{b}.BAK@{ub} files in the outbound directory.
     If a backup list is loaded (when the @{b}.REQ@{ub} file for a node is not
     found) a proper message will be displayed.

     @{b}Scan inbound after poll@{ub} will force @{b}MUI-FReq@{ub} to scan the inbound
     directory for received files just after polling a node.

     @{b}Save list before quitting@{ub} will cause the program to save the
     current filelist before quitting. Normally, you have to do it by
     hand.

     @{b}Convert filenames to uppercase@{ub} will cause every name inserted in
     the filelist to be converted in uppercase. Some Fidonet file
     requester server need an uppercase name to work properly
     (especially those running on MS-DOS systems).

   @{b}*@{ub} The actions gadgets. They are:

     @{b}Save@{ub} will save the configuration, so it will be loaded at program
     startup.

     @{b}Use@{ub} will use this configuration, but when you quit the program it
     will be lost.


@EndNode

